<div id="articleHeader">
<img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20081227044832im_/http://cache.boston.com/bonzai-fba/File-Based_Image_Resource/from_provider_ap.gif" alt="The Associated Press" title="The Associated Press" height="20" width="100" border="0" class="providerlogo" align="right"/>

<h1>Family sues over fatal car crash on railroad tracks</h1>





<p class="byline"><span></span> <span class="date">December 27, 2006</span></p>
</div>

<div id="articleGraphs">
<div id="page1"><p><span>NEW LONDON, Conn.&nbsp;--</span>Relatives of a grandmother and two children who were killed last year at a Waterford railroad crossing have filed a federal lawsuit against Amtrak and others.</p><p>Patricia Metzermacher, 62, and her two grandchildren, 8-year-old Zachary Metzermacher and 4-year-old Courtney Metzermacher, died after the grandmother's car was struck by a train traveling 70 miles an hour through the street-level crossing on Miner Lane.</p><p>The car was dragged more than 1,000 feet. The grandmother was driving Zachary to his school bus stop on the corner of Miner Lane, which was less than a mile from their house at 75 Miner Lane.</p><p>Patricia and Zachary were killed instantly, and Courtney, who was in a child seat in the back seat of her grandmother's car, lived for several days before her parents decided to authorize doctors to remove life support.</p><p>The family members have filed a wrongful death lawsuit in U.S. District Court in New Haven against Amtrak, the town of Waterford, planning director Thomas Wagner, two former first selectmen and the police chief.</p><p>The lawsuit claims the railroad and town officials knew the railroad crossing was dangerous but neglected to fix it for 20 years.</p><p>Wagner, the town planner, witnessed the accident as he waited for the train to pass. He says Metzermacher's car drifted slowly toward the tracks and did not stop. He says the car's hood was below the gates.</p><p>The lawyer for the Metzermachers says the crossing gates malfunctioned the day of the accident, trapping the car in the train's path.</p><p>------</p><p>Information from: The Day, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20081227044832/http://www.theday.com/">http://<a target="_new" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20081227044832/http://www.theday.com/">www.theday.com</a></a><img class="storyend" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20081227044832im_/http://cache.boston.com/bonzai-fba/File-Based_Image_Resource/dingbat_story_end_icon.gif" width="6" height="8" border="0" alt=""/></p>
<div class="copyright">&copy; Copyright 2006 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed.</div>
</div>
</div>







